I. Executive Summary
Tri-State Generation and Transmission Association (“Tri-State”) is a not-for-profit
generation and transmission electric cooperative which supplies power, on a wholesale
basis, to its forty-one member distribution cooperatives and public power districts
(“distribution members" or “members”or “Utility Members”). Tri-State serves its
distribution members' power requirements pursuant to long-term, all-requirements
Wholesale Electric Service Contracts (“WESC”). Tri-State’s distribution members, in
turn, supply power on a retail basis to their members.
Tri-State is owned entirely by its members, which are the primary purchasers of the power
that Tri-State sells. Tri-State has two classes of members. Tri-State’s Class A members
are the forty-one electric distribution members named above. Tri-State has three non-
utility members who do not take electric service from Tri-State. Tri-State is governed by
its Board of Directors (Board) which includes a representative from each of Tri-State’s
41 distribution members.
Tri-State’s charges to its distribution members under the proposed A-41 Rate are
determined by the formula rate contained herein, which is applied to the sales of demand
and energy made to each of the distribution members. The formula rate recovers Tri-
State’s cost of service, including a defined margin requirement to meet lender covenants
and amounts required by Board Policy 503. As described below in the “True-up
Provision”, additional margins may be recovered from time-to-time to be used for rate
stabilization to its members. Refunds may occur in the event of over-collection of
margins. The formula rate collects revenues based on budgeted cost estimates with true-
up mechanisms to ensure that all costs, including Board-approved margins, are collected.
Accumulated margins represent Tri-State's equity. They are allocated to the distribution
members and subsequently returned to the members in accordance with Board Policy
503. Differences between required margins and actual margins are either collected or
refunded in accordance with this rate schedule. Tri-State’s budget is developed annually.
The annual budget is approved by the Board.TRI-STATE RATE SCHEDULE
Generation and Transmission A-41
Association, Inc.
Page 2
A. Development and Implementation of the Formula Rate
The process of preparing, reviewing and revising the amounts to be included in the
formula rate begins with the development of a calendar year budget which typically is
submitted to the Board for its approval by September of the prior year. The approved
budget is the basis for Tri-State’s revenue requirements and loads which are included in
the formula rate. The formula rate will typically be placed into effect January 1, which is
the beginning of the budget year. The Board will monitor ongoing performance and
should circumstances arise, the Board may approve an updated budget to become
effective during the same year. Rate updates must follow the notice requirements under
the members’WESCs.
The specific steps involved in developing and implementing the formula rate include:
1. Forecasting of power supply requirements;
2. Development and approval of the budget; and
3. Inclusion of the budget in the formula rate.
1. Forecasting of Power Supply Requirements
The budgeting process begins with preparation of a projection of the annual loads (kW
of demand and kWh of energy) to be supplied by Tri-State to each of the distribution
members during the budget period. The projected loads are first developed by Tri-State,
with each member given the opportunity to provide input and review before the load
projections are finalized.
2. Development and Approval of the Budget
After forecasting loads, the budget is developed. The budget considers Tri-State’s costs
associated with providing power supply service to its distribution members, including
power generation and purchase costs, transmission ownership and purchase costs, interest
charges, administrative and general expenses, certain present and projected rates under
Tri-State’s Open Access Transmission Tariff (“OATT”), and margins. Budgeted costs
are developed by Tri-State staff and are demonstrated in accounts defined by the Federal
Energy Regulatory Commission (“FERC”) Uniform System of Accounts (“USoA”). The
budget is then presented to the Board and, after review and discussion, is approved.
3. Inclusion of the Budget in the Formula RateTRI-STATE RATE SCHEDULE
Generation and Transmission A-41
Association, Inc.
Page 3
After the Board's approval of the budget, the resulting projected loads and costs are
included in the formula rate contained herein.
B. True-up Provision
The A-41 Rate contains an annual true-up provision. The true-up adjustment is
determined to ensure that Tri-State does not either under-collect or over-collect its
required margins. Following the end of each calendar year as a part of the year-end audit
process, Tri-State will calculate its revenues, expenses, and margins for the subject
calendar year. Such calculation will be made before any true-up adjustment has been
determined. The results of the true-up calculations will be presented to the Board for
approval. If the Tri-State Board determines that the total margins, including operating
and non-operating margins, are either greater than or less than its margin requirement, a
true-up will be administered. The Board-approved true-up will be recorded in the subject
calendar year and will impact revenues so that the required margin levels are achieved.
The true-up amount will be allocated among the Utility Members on a pro-rata basis,
using the total revenue billed under the Class A rate to each member during the rate year.
In the event of under-collection, or shortfall, the additional required revenue will be
satisfied by a combination of: i) increased usage of reserved revenues, as approved by the
Board, and ii) additional revenues from the distribution members collected in twelve
equal monthly amounts during the calendar year following the year of the calculation. As
an example, if Tri-State determines in 2025 that additional member revenue is required
to meet the margin requirements for 2024, the members will be charged twelve, equal
monthly amounts during the 2026 calendar year. In the event of an over-collection and
there is a refund to the members, the refund amount will be returned in twelve, equal
monthly amounts during the 2026 calendar year. The Board will determine whether any
portion of the over-collection should be retained for the purpose of future rate
stabilization. Amounts eligible for retention include extraordinary revenues such as
amounts received from Contract Termination Payments (“CTP”), sales of assets,
government grants, etc.TRI-STATE RATE SCHEDULE

Note F Margin Requirement

III. Rate Design and Development of Charges
A. Rate Design
1. Demand Rates
Demand rates shall be developed annually to collect, through the formula rate contained
herein, demand charges as estimated in Tri-State's budget. Each distribution member shall
be charged monthly based on its TPP/MCP demand billing units, as defined in Section III.B
Application of Charges, multiplied by demand rates for the following, rounded to two
decimal places:
a. Generation Demand Service
i. Generation Demand Service
The $/kW Generation Service Rate is calculated as:
Generation Demand Rate ($/kW) = (Annual Carrying Cost / kW CT /12)
Where:
Total Capacity Cost = Overnight Capital Cost of a CT-Aeroderivative at price levels as
reported by the U.S. Energy Information Administration1 plus a general plant adder.
Capital Cost for a CT-Aeroderivative will be multiplied by the Handy Whitman Index
(“HWI”) applicable to FERC plant account No, 344, Plateau Region and using the most
recent HWI at the time of Budget development. The general plant adder is equal to (Total
Generation Demand Gross Plant in Service)/ (Total Generation Demand Gross Plant in
Service less Generation Demand General Plant in Service and Generation Demand
Intangible Plant in Service). All values used in the General Plant adder calculation are
from Schedule 2.
Annual Carrying Cost = Total Capital Cost is converted into an annual carrying cost which
includes AFDUC, interest expense, depreciation expense, operation and maintenance
costs plus an administration and general expense adder and margins. Depreciation
expense is calculated using a 40-year operating life for a CT-Aeroderivative as reported
by the U.S. Energy Information Administration. CT-Aeroderivative operation and
maintenance costs are as reported by the U.S. Energy Information Administration.
Operation and Maintenance costs will be multiplied by the most recent Consumers Price
Index (CPI-U US City Average). The administration and general expense adder is equal
to (Total Generation Demand Operation and Maintenance Expense)/(Total Generation
Demand Operation and Maintenance Expense less Generation Demand Administration
and General Expenses). All values used in the administration and general expense adder
calculation are from Schedule 1.
1
Initially from Capital Cost and Performance Characteristic Estimates for Utility Scale Electric Power
Generating Technologies, January 2024 and updated annually thereafter.TRI-STATE RATE SCHEDULE
Generation and Transmission A-41
Association, Inc.
Page 11
kW CT is the unit capacity of the CT-Aeroderivative resource as contained in the Energy
Information Administration report.
b. Transmission Network Demand Service
i. Transmission Network Demand Service
The $/kW Transmission Network Service Rate is calculated as:
Transmission Network Demand Rate ($/kW) =
(Annual Budgeted Transmission Network
Expenses) / TPP/MCP kW
Where:
Annual Budgeted Transmission Network Expenses are costs as developed in the Formula.
Schedule 1 and 5.
TPP/MCP kW is the sum for the Budget year of the projected Members’highest thirty
(30) minute integrated total demand for load subject to the formula rate for all of the
Member’s Points of Delivery measured in each monthly billing period during the Tri-
State Peak Period. The Tri-State Peak Period is defined as the time period from 1:00 PM
through 9:00 PM (the billing ½ hour period ending 1:30 PM through the billing ½ hour
period ending at 9:00 PM) daily, Monday through Saturday, with the exception of the
following six (6) holidays if occurring on Monday through Saturday: New Year’s Day,
Memorial Day, Independence Day, Labor Day, Thanksgiving Day and Christmas Day.
c. Transmission Non-Network Demand Service
i. Transmission Non-Network Demand Service
The $/kW Transmission Non-Network Service Rate is calculated as:
Transmission Non-Network Demand Rate ($/kW) =
(Annual Budgeted Transmission Non-Network
Expenses) / TPP/MCP kW
Where:
Annual Budgeted Transmission Non-Network Expenses are costs as developed in the
Formula, Schedule 1 and 5.TRI-STATE RATE SCHEDULE
Generation and Transmission A-41
Association, Inc.
Page 12
TPP/MCP kW is the sum for the Budget year of the projected Members’highest thirty
(30) minute integrated total demand for load subject to the formula rate for all of the
Member’s Points of Delivery measured in each monthly billing period during the Tri-
State Peak Period. The Tri-State Peak Period is defined as the time period from 1:00 PM
(noon) through 9:00 PM (the billing ½ hour period ending 1:30 PM through the billing ½
hour period ending at 9:00 PM) daily, Monday through Saturday, with the exception of
the following six (6) holidays if occurring on Monday through Saturday: New Year’s
Day, Memorial Day, Independence Day, Labor Day, Thanksgiving Day and Christmas
Day.
If delivery of that portion of service purchased by Tri-State from the Western Area Power
Administration (WAPA) is made over the facilities of a third party and the costs for that

A-12, the cost of such transmission service as applicable to deliveries of WAPA power
shall continue to be borne by the Member System.
d. Ancillary Services Demand Service

iii) Schedule 3 Regulating Reserve; iv) Schedule 5 Spinning Reserve;

Ancillary Service Demand Rate ($/kW) =
(Annual Budgeted Ancillary Service Expenses) /
TPP/MCP kW
Where:
Annual Budgeted Ancillary Service Expenses are costs as developed in the Formula,
Schedule 1 and 5.
For determination of the rates for Schedules 1 and 2, the TPP/MCP kW is the same as
used for Transmission Network and Transmission Non-Network Service Demand
Service.
For determination of the rates for Schedules 3, 4, and 6, the TPP/MCP kW is the same as

2. Energy Rate
a. Generation Energy Service
The Generation Energy Rate shall be developed annually to collect Generation Energy
Costs as developed in Tri-State's Budget and Cost of Service, plus the difference between
the total Generation Demand related expenses determined by the Cost of Service and
annual Generation Demand Revenues derived from the Demand Rate, the result being
“Net Generation Energy Cost”. Generation Demand Revenues shall equal the Generation
Demand Rate multiplied by the annual Generation TPP/MCP kW. Utility Member shall
be charged monthly based on its monthly energy usage multiplied by the applicable
Generation Energy Rate. The Generation Energy Rate shall be rounded to five decimal
places.
Generation Energy Rate ($/kWh) = (Annual Budgeted Energy Expenses + Net
Generation Energy Cost) /kWh.
Where:
Annual Budgeted Energy Expenses are costs as developed in the Formula, Schedule 1.
Net Generation Energy Cost is the difference between the total Generation Demand
related expenses and Generation Demand revues as determined by the Formula, Schedule
5.
kWh is the sum for the Budget year of the projected kWh energy sales to Members under
the formula rate.
b. Ancillary Services Energy Service
i.Ancillary service energy charges shall be separately calculated for each
of the following –i) Schedule 4 Energy Imbalance; and ii) Schedule 9
Generator Imbalance.
Ancillary Service Energy Rates ($/kWh) =
(Annual Budgeted Ancillary Service Expenses) /
kWh
Where:
Annual Budgeted Ancillary Service Expenses are costs as developed in the Formula,
Schedule 1 and 5.
kWh is the sum for the Budget year of the projected kWh energy sales to Members under
the formula rate.TRI-STATE RATE SCHEDULE

3. Standby Rate
Rate Schedule S is applicable to a distribution member with any customer that requires
Standby Service of more than one (1) MW, and less than or equal to five (5) MW. Tri-
State will provide wholesale standby electric power to its member, who will then provide
standby service to the customer via retail rate arrangements. The Standby Rate consists
of monthly charges that depend on whether the generation is dispatchable or not.
The rate components of Rate Schedule S are dependent upon the demand and energy
charges determined by the Class A Formula Rate. Rate Schedule S contains the formulas
and the defined terms used to develop the monthly charges applicable to a member taking
standby service from Tri-State, and the formulas are not re-stated here.
B. Application of Charges
All Demand and Energy Charges shall be calculated at the Point of Delivery level with
each kW and kWh determinant being derived from revenue quality meters located at each
Point of Delivery. These delivery points are the demarcation points whereby Tri-State is
obligated to deliver electric power and energy to a Member System. Each Point of
Delivery shall be as specified in Schedule B of Tri-State’s WESC with a Member System.
If the metering is remote from the Point of Delivery, appropriate increases to the demand
and energy meter readings will be agreed upon between Tri-State and the Member
System. Transformer losses applied to such meter readings shall be determined pursuant
to Board of Directors Policy 109.
Member’s Tri-State Peak Period/Member Coincident Peak Billing Demand
(“TPP/MCP”) shall be determined as the Member’s highest thirty (30) minute integrated
total demand measured in each monthly billing period during the Tri-State Peak Period.
For Members receiving service at more than one Point of Delivery, the demand shall be
the maximum coincident peak demand for all of the Member’s Points of Delivery, the
same as if the service were provided to the Member at one Point of Delivery. The Tri-
State Peak Period is defined as the time period from 1:00 PM (noon) through 9:00 PM
(the billing ½ hour period ending 1:30 PM through the billing ½ hour period ending at
9:00 PM) daily, Monday through Saturday, with the exception of the following six (6)
holidays if occurring on Monday through Saturday: New Year’s Day, Memorial Day,
Independence Day, Labor Day, Thanksgiving Day and Christmas Day.
If the Member has distributed generation resources that have been developed in
accordance with Board Policy 115, the TPP/MCP applicable to Generation Demand
Service is reduced by the output of the generation that occurs during the hour the billing
demand is established.
C. Payment TermsTRI-STATE RATE SCHEDULE
Generation and Transmission A-41
Association, Inc.
Page 15
A bill for electric service shall be presented to the Member no later than the 20th day of
the month following the month in which the electric service was consumed. The date of
the bill shall be deemed the date of presentation. Electric service furnished hereunder shall
be paid in useable funds at the office of the Seller in Westminster, Colorado (or such other
location as Seller may designate), monthly, no later than the last day of the calendar month
in which the bill is mailed to the Member provided however, if the date of presentation of
the bill falls after the 20th day of the month, the Member shall receive one day of delay
in payment for each day of delay in presentation.1

Member Formula Rate Implementation Protocols
Section I Annual Update
1. The Formula Rate Template of Tri-State Generation and Transmission Association, Inc. (“Tri-
State”) and these Formula Rate Implementation Protocols (“Protocols”) together comprise the
filed rate (“Formula Rate”) of Tri-State for service provided to Members under Wholesale
Electric Service Contracts (“WESC”). Tri-State must follow the instructions specified in the
Formula Rate to calculate its Projected Annual Revenue Requirements (“PARR”) and the rates
for Class A service to its Members. The PARR shall be determined by using the Board-
approved Budget for the rate year. The Formula Rate shall become effective for recovery of
Tri-State’s PARR upon the Effective Date.
2. The Formula Rate shall be applicable to service on and after January 1 of each calendar Year
through December 31 of that same year. (“Rate Year”).
3. On or before October 1 of each Calendar Year, Tri-State shall:
(a) Recalculate the PARR and the rates for WESC service for the new Rate Year in
accordance with the Formula Rate (“Annual Update”); and
(b) Provide that Annual Update to the Tri-State Members; and
4. The date on which the last of the events listed in Section 1.3(a) or 1.3(b) occurs shall be that
year’s (“Posting Date.”)
Section II Mid-Year Update
1. The Tri-State Board may review and revise the budget during the Rate Year. In the event of a
budget revision, the PARR shall be updated and determined by using the Board-approved
revised Budget for the Rate Year. The Formula Rate shall become effective for recovery of
Tri-State’s updated PARR upon an Effective Date approved by the Board.
2. The Formula Rate shall be applicable to service on the Effective Date through December 31
of that same year.
Section III True-Up
1. On or before May 15 of each Calendar Year, Tri-State shall:
(a) Recalculate the margin for service for the Rate Year using actual values available from
the books and records of Tri-State and compare to financial metrics required in Board
Policy 503 per the Tariff; and
(b) Record the change in any budgeted deferred revenue, and Member revenues, up or
down, in the Rate Year with an offsetting amount to Member revenues recorded as a
regulatory asset or liability as appropriate; and
(c) Provide that information to the Members receiving service under the rate (True-up
Posting Date)2
2. Tri-State shall provide a notice of such posting via an email distribution to all Members.
3. The true-up amount shall be included as part of the independently audited books and records
of Tri-State for the Rate Year.;
4. Within thirty (30) days of the True-up Posting date of Tri-State’s Annual True-up, Tri-State
will host an in-person or virtual meeting, limited to Members, to discuss the Annual True-up.
Tri-State shall provide notice of this meeting concurrent with the posting of the Formula Rate
True-up. The notice shall include the date, time and location of the true-up meeting. The True-
up meeting shall also be available by telephone and/or web access with all meeting materials
provided.
A. Information Exchange
1. Members may begin submitting information requests immediately following the True-Up
Posting Date of the annual rate true-up and will have until sixty (60) days after the date of the
True-up posting to serve information requests on Tri-State for information and work papers
supporting the annual true-up. Such information requests shall be limited to what is reasonably
necessary to determine:
(a) The extent or effect of an accounting change;
(b) Whether the annual true-up fails to include data properly recorded in accordance with
the Protocols and the accuracy and consistency of data;
(c) The proper application of the Formula Rate and procedures in these Protocols;
(d) The effect of any change to the underlying Uniform System of Accounts or Formula
Rate; or
(e) Any other information that may reasonably have a substantive effect on the calculation
of the charges pursuant to the Formula Rate.
The information and document requests shall not otherwise be directed to ascertain whether
the Formula Rate is just and reasonable.
2. Tri-State shall make a good faith effort to respond to information requests pertaining to the
Annual Update within fifteen (15) business days of receipt.
3. Tri-State shall provide to all Members all information requests received and Tri-State’s
response(s) to such requests. If responses to information requests contain information deemed
by Tri-State to be confidential, such information will not be shared with other members but
will be made available to requesting parties pursuant to a confidentiality agreement executed
by the requesting party and Tri-State.
B. Informal Challenge Procedures
1. Members shall have until August 1 to make specific “Informal Challenges.”The Informal
Challenge must specify the inputs, supporting explanations, allocations, calculations, or other
information to which the Member objects and provide an appropriate explanation and
documents to support its Informal Challenge. Tri-State will make a good faith effort to respond
to any Informal Challenge within twenty (20) days of notification of such Informal Challenge.3
Tri-State shall appoint representatives to work with the Member to resolve the Informal
Challenge.
2. Tri-State will provide to all Members all Informal Challenges from Individual Members and
Tri-State’s responses to the Informal Challenges. If responses to information requests contain
information deemed by Tri-State to be confidential, such information will not be publicly
posted but will be made available to requesting parties pursuant to a confidentiality agreement
executed by the requesting party and Tri-State.
3. Any changes or adjustments to the Annual True-up resulting from the Information Exchange
and Informal Challenge procedures that are agreed to by Tri-State and resolved prior to the end
of the review period shall be reported in the final notification to Members. Any changes or
adjustments agreed to by Tri-State after this date will be reported in the Informational Filing
made with FERC and will be reflected in the Annual Rate True-up for the following Rate Year.
C. Formal Challenges.
1. A Formal Challenge can be made after exhausting the informal challenge process and shall:
(a) Clearly, and with particularity identify the action or inaction which is alleged to violate
the filed Formula Rate or Protocols;
(b) Explain how the action or inaction violates the filed Formula Rate or Protocols;
(c) Set forth the business, commercial, economic or other issues presented by the action or
inaction as such relate to or affect the party filing the Formal Challenge, including:
i. The extent or effect of an accounting change;
ii. Whether the Annual Update fails to include data properly recorded in accordance
with the Protocols and the accuracy and consistency of data;
iii. The proper application of the Formula Rate and procedures in these Protocols;
iv. The effect of any change to the underlying Uniform System of Accounts or
Formula Rate; or
v. Any other information that may reasonably have a substantive effect on the
calculation of the charges pursuant to the Formula Rate.
(d) Make a good faith effort to quantify the financial impact or burden (if any) created for
the party filing the Formal Challenge as a result of the action or inaction;
(e) State whether the issues presented are pending in an existing proceeding in any forum
in which the Member is a party, and if so, provide an explanation why timely resolution
cannot be achieved in that forum;
(f) State the specific relief or remedy requested, including any request for stay or extension
of time, and the basis for that relief;
(g) Include all documents that support the facts in the Formal Challenge in possession of,
or otherwise attainable by, the Member, including, but not limited to, contracts and
affidavits; and
(h) State whether the filing party utilized the Informal Challenge procedures described in
these Protocols with regard to any issue.
2. Formal Challenges shall be filed with FERC either in the FERC Docket assigned to the
Informational Filing or via Section 206 of the FPA, and shall be served upon Tri-State
contemporaneously with the filing at FERC. Service can be accomplished by electronic mail4
in accordance with § 385.2010(f) (3), express delivery or messenger to the individual listed as
the contact person in Tri-State’Informational Filing.
D. Modification of Formula Rate or Annual Update
1. No Member shall seek to modify the Formula Rate under the challenge procedures (either
Formal or Informal) set forth in these Protocols and the Annual Update shall not be subject to
challenge for the purpose of modifying the Formula Rate or the Board approved budget data
used as inputs in the Annual Update process.
2. A change to the Formula Rate fixed inputs related to depreciation rates and amortization
periods may not be made absent the appropriate filing with FERC pursuant to the FPA Sections
205 or 206.
3. If Tri-State makes a correction to a Mistake in its financial information during a Rate Year that
would affect the Formula Rate for that Rate Year, such corrections and any resulting refunds
or surcharges shall be reflected in the annual update for the next effective Rate Year. For
purposes of these Protocols, “Mistake”shall mean errors or omissions regarding the values
input into the Formula Rate template, such as arithmetic or computational errors. Mistakes
shall not include matters involving exercise of judgment or substantive differences of opinion
regarding the derivation of an input that is more properly the subject of the annual review
process.
4. Any changes to the data inputs or as the result of a FERC proceeding shall be incorporated into
the Formula Rate template and the charges produced by the Formula Rate in the Annual Update
for the next effective Rate Year.
E. FERC Informational Filing.
1. By October 15th of each year, Tri-State shall submit to FERC an informational filing
(“Informational Filing”) of its Annual True-up.
2. This Informational Filing must include the information that is reasonably necessary to
determine:
(a) That input data under the Formula Rate is properly recorded in any underlying work
papers; (b) The accuracy of the data and the consistency with the Formula Rate of the ARR
and rates under review; and
(c) The extent of accounting changes that affect Formula Rate inputs.
3. The Informational Filing must also describe all aspects of the Formula Rate or its inputs that
are the subject of an ongoing dispute under the Informal or Formal Challenge procedures.
4. Contemporaneous with the making of such Informational Filing, Tri-State shall provide notice
of the Informational Filing to Members via an email distribution to all Members.

1.0 DESCRIPTION:
A rate that is applicable to Tri-State Member Systems that have customers with Self-Generation
that receive Standby Service.
2.0 PURPOSE:
This rate reflects the valuation of Standby Service provided to Tri-State Member Systems that have
customers who operate Self-Generation for the purpose of serving their own load.
3.0 APPLICABILITY:
This Rate Schedule S will apply to a Member System with any customer that requires Standby
Service of more than one (1) MW. Standby Service Rates for customers requiring Standby Service
in excess of five (5) MW may be adjusted by Tri-State and will be based on the specific
circumstances of the Self-Generation including operating characteristics, balancing authority
arrangements and other factors.
This Rate Schedule S will not apply to Member Systems with customers under sale for resale
contracts who operate Self-Generation, Member Systems with customers that have onsite
generation normally used for emergency supply or for Member Systems with generators that are
subject to Policy 115 generation contracts.
For a Member System customer load that is partially served by Self-Generation, the remaining
customer load will be included for billing under the prevailing Class A Rate.

Demand and energy delivered during unscheduled outages or curtailments for Member
System customers requiring Standby Service for dispatchable generation and all
delivered demand and energy for Member System customers requiring Standby
Service for non-dispatchable generation.
5.6 Billing Period:
The period of time between the consecutive monthly meter reading dates used by Tri-State
to determine billing quantities. The billing period will normally coincide with a calendar
month.
5.7 Gross Customer Demand:
The total demand determined by meter measurement equal to the total demand requirement
of the customer, regardless of whether such demand is supplied by the customer’s Self-
Generation.
5.8 Point of Delivery:
A point at which Tri-State is obligated to deliver electric power and energy to a Member
System. Each Point of Delivery shall be as specified in Schedule B of Tri-State’s
Wholesale Electric Service Contract with a Member System.TRI-STATE RATE SCHEDULE

5.9 Reservation Demand Charge:
A fixed monthly charge applied to the Reserved Capacity.
5.10 Reservation Energy Charge:
A charge applied to energy generated by a non-dispatchable
facility.
5.11 Reserved Capacity:
The amount of Standby Service, in kilowatts, required by a Member System’s customer
who operates Self-Generation. The amount of Reserved Capacity is typically equal to the
rated capacity of the Self-Generation facility.
5.12 Scheduled Maintenance:
An outage of predetermined length that is communicated to Tri-State at least one week in
advance. Scheduled Maintenance will be permitted for a maximum of 336 hours
per year, but may not occur during the months of January, February, July, August
or September.
5.13 Scheduled Maintenance Energy Charge:
A charge for service provided during a scheduled maintenance
outage.
5.14 Self-Generation:
Electrical generation that is located behind the retail meter, the output of which is used to
serve that customer’s load, in whole or in part.
5.15 Service Charge:
A fixed monthly charge to recover administration and
implementation costs.
5.16 Standby Demand:
The measured Standby Service demand quantity, in kilowatts, that is delivered during an
unscheduled outage or curtailment of the customer’s Self-Generation facility. For any
Member System’s customer receiving service at more than one point, the Standby Demand
shall be the sum of the Standby Demand for all such points. If the measured Standby
Service demand quantity delivered exceeds the Reserved Capacity, then the Reserved
Capacity shall be adjusted, prospectively, to reflect the larger Standby Service demand
quantity.TRI-STATE RATE SCHEDULE

5.17 Standby Energy:
The total monthly quantity of kilowatt-hours of energy delivered during each 30-minute
integration period associated with Standby Demand used by a Member System’s customer
when the customer’s Self-Generation unit is off-line or generating less than the Reserved
Capacity during a monthly billing period.
5.18 Standby Service:
Electric service held in reserve by Tri-State for its Member System’s customer to replace
electric service ordinarily generated by the customer’s Self-Generation unit during times
when the unit(s) is / are off-line or generating less than the Reserved Capacity.
5.19 Tri-State Peak Period:
The time period from 1:00 PM (noon) through 9:00 PM (the billing ½ hour period ending
1:30 PM through the billing ½ hour period ending at 9:00 PM) daily, Monday through
Saturday, with the exception of the following six (6) holidays if occurring on Monday
through Saturday: New Year’s Day, Memorial Day, Independence Day, Labor Day,
Thanksgiving Day and Christmas Day.
5.20 Tri-State Peak Period/Member Coincident Peak Billing Demand (TPP/MCP)
The Member System’s highest thirty (30) minute integrated total demand measured in each
monthly billing period during the Tri-State Peak Period. For Member Systems receiving
service at more than one Point of Delivery, the demand shall be the maximum coincident
peak demand for all of the Member’s Points of Delivery, the same as if the service were
provided to the Member System as one Point of Delivery.
6.0 GENERAL CONDITIONS:
6.1 Metering/Documentation:
Member System shall install, or cause to be installed, metering and recording device(s), or
equivalent, to measure generation from each Standby Service customer’s Self-Generation
facility, as well as customer load. Such metering and recording device(s) shall be of a type
and accuracy acceptable to Tri-State. Such metering and recording device(s) shall: (a) be
capable of measuring and registering energy used and generated; (b) be capable of
measuring and recording thirty (30) minute integrated demand for each thirty (30) minute
time interval; and (c) shall have sufficient recording capability or memory to store at least
thirty-six (36) days of thirty (30) minute integrated demand data. Depending on the size
of the generator, real-time metering and telemetry may be required. Data from such
metering and recording device(s) shall be provided to Tri-State in a format that can beTRI-STATE RATE SCHEDULE
